'''Bristol''' ({{Audio|en-uk-Bristol.ogg|pronunciation}}; {{pronEng|<U+02C8>br<U+026A>st<U+0259>l}}) is a [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]], [[unitary authority area]] and [[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] in [[South West England]], {{convert|105|mi|km|0}} west of London, and {{convert|44|mi|km|0}} east of [[Cardiff]].

With an estimated population of 416,400 for the unitary authority in mid-2007,<ref name=ons-pop>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Product.asp?vlnk=15106
|title=Population estimates for UK, England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland - current datasets
|publisher=National Statistics Online
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and a surrounding [[urban area]] with an estimated 561,500 residents,<ref name=ons-pop /> it is England's sixth, and the United Kingdom's eighth most populous city, one of England's [[English Core Cities Group|core cities]] and the most populous city in [[South West England]]. It received a [[Royal Charter]] in 1155 and was granted County status in 1373. From the 13th century, for half a millennium, it ranked amongst the top three English cities after London, alongside [[York]] and [[Norwich]],<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/188048/English-language/74812/Transition-from-Middle-English-to-Early-Modern-English
|title=Transition from Middle English to Early Modern EnglishBritannica Online Encyclopedia
|publisher=Britannica Online Encyclopedia
|accessdate=2009-03-14
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> until the rapid rise of [[Liverpool]], [[Birmingham]] and [[Manchester]] during the [[Industrial Revolution]] in the latter part of the 18th century. It borders the [[Ceremonial county|counties]] of [[Somerset]] and [[Gloucestershire]], also located near the historic cities of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] to the south east and [[Gloucester]] to the north. The city is built around the [[River Avon, Bristol|River Avon]], and it also has a short coastline on the estuary of the [[River Severn]] where it flows into the [[Bristol Channel]].

Bristol is the largest centre of culture, employment and education in the region. Its prosperity has been linked with the sea since its earliest days. The commercial [[Port of Bristol]] was originally in the city centre before being moved to the [[Severn Estuary]] at [[Avonmouth]]; [[Royal Portbury Dock]] is on the western edge of the city boundary. In more recent years the economy has depended on the [[aerospace]] industry, and the city centre docks have been regenerated as a centre of heritage and culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2007/oct/30/property |title=Bristol: seemingly unstoppable growth |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-12-18 | publisher=The Guardian | date= 30 October 2007}}</ref>  There are 34 other populated places on Earth [[List of places called Bristol|named Bristol]], most in the [[United States]], but also in [[Peru]], [[Canada]], [[Jamaica]] and [[Costa Rica]], all presumably commemorating the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geody.com/geolook.php?world=terra&map=col&q=bristol&subm1=submit|title=Bristol on Geody|work=Geody|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article5409039.ece|title=Richmond, in Surrey, is the most widely copied British place name worldwide|work=Times Online|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref>

==Boundaries==
{| style="float:right;" 
 | [[Image:Clifton.bridge.arp.750pix.jpg|thumb|left|[[Isambard Kingdom Brunel|Brunel]]'s [[Clifton Suspension Bridge]].]]
 |}

There are a number of different ways in which Bristol's boundaries are defined, depending on whether the boundaries attempt to define the city, the built-up area, or the wider "[[Greater Bristol]]". The narrowest definition of the city is the [[Bristol City Council|city council]] boundary, which takes in a large section of the [[Severn Estuary]] west as far as, but not including, the islands of [[Steep Holm]] and [[Flat Holm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/keystats/sqmap.aspx?kv=1312817302&type=-1&title=Bristol%3b+City+of+UA+|title=NOMIS (www.nomisweb.co.uk) area boundary for the Bristol unitary authority|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref> A slightly less narrow definition is used by the [[Office for National Statistics]] (ONS); this includes built-up areas which adjoin Bristol but are not within the city council boundary, such as [[Whitchurch, Bristol|Whitchurch]] village, [[Filton]], [[Patchway]], [[Bradley Stoke]], and excludes non-built-up areas within the city council boundary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/keystats/sqmap.aspx?kv=1371537983&type=-1&title=Bristol+Urban+Area+-+Bristol+(urban+area+subdivisions)|title= NOMIS (www.nomisweb.co.uk) area boundary for the Bristol urban area|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref>  The ONS has also defined an area called the "Bristol Urban Area", which includes [[Kingswood, South Gloucestershire|Kingswood]], [[Mangotsfield]], [[Stoke Gifford]], [[Winterbourne, Gloucestershire|Winterbourne]], [[Frampton Cotterell]], [[Almondsbury]] and [[Easton-in-Gordano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/Expodata/Spreadsheets/D8271.xls|title=Usual resident population: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas|format=xls|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref> The term "Greater Bristol", used for example by the Government Office of the South West,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwesteip.co.uk/downloads/documents/sts.pdf|title=Greater Bristol Strategic Transport Study|last=Atkins|date=2005|publisher=South West Regional Assembly|format=PDF|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-02-05}}</ref> usually refers to the area occupied by the city and parts of the three neighbouring local authorities ([[Bath and North East Somerset]], [[North Somerset]] and [[South Gloucestershire]]), an area sometimes also known as the "former [[Avon (county)|Avon]] area" or the "[[West of England]]".

==History==
{{main|History of Bristol}}
[[Archaeological]] finds believed to be 60,000&nbsp;years old, discovered at [[Shirehampton]] and [[St Annes, Bristol|St Annes]], provide evidence of settlement in the Bristol area from the [[Palaeolithic]] era.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Local-History-Heritage/archaeology/palaeolithic-in-bristol.en |title=The Palaeolithic in Bristol | publisher=Bristol City Council | date= 24 April 2007 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-06 }}</ref> 
There are [[Iron Age]] [[hill fort]]s near the city, at [[Leigh Woods]] and [[Clifton Down]] on the side of the [[Avon Gorge]], and on [[Kingsweston Hill]], near [[Henbury]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Local-History-Heritage/archaeology/bristol-in-the-iron-age.en |title=Bristol in the Iron Age |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10 |publisher=Bristol City Council }}</ref>
During the [[Roman Britain|Roman era]] there was a settlement, ''Abona'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roman-britain.org/places/abona.htm |title=ABONA - Major Romano-British Settlement |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-17 |publisher=www.Roman-Britain.org }}</ref> 
at what is now [[Sea Mills, Bristol|Sea Mills]], connected to [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] by a [[Roman road]], and another at the present-day [[Inns Court]]. There were also isolated [[Roman villa]]s and small [[Roman fort]]s and settlements throughout the area.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Bristol City Council | url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Local-History-Heritage/archaeology/bristol-in-the-roman-period.en | title=Bristol in the Roman Period |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref>
The town of ''Brycgstow'' ([[Old English language|Old English]], "the place at the bridge")<ref>{{cite book |last=Little |first=Bryan |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=The City and County of Bristol |year=1967 |publisher=S. R. Publishers |location=Wakefield |isbn=0854095128 }}</ref> existed by the beginning of the 11th century, and under [[Normans|Norman]] rule acquired one of the strongest [[Bristol Castle|castles]] in southern England.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Bristol Past | url=http://www.buildinghistory.org/bristol/castle.shtml | title=The Impregnable City |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-10-07}}</ref>

[[Image:Bristol harbour arp 750pix.jpg|thumb|left|[[Bristol Bridge]] seen across the harbour]]
The area around the the original junction of the [[River_Frome,_Bristol|River Frome]] with the [[River Avon, Bristol|River Avon]], adjacent to the original [[Bristol Bridge]] and just outside the town walls, was where the port began to develop in the eleventh century.<ref name="Brace">{{cite book |last=Brace |first=Keith |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Portrait of Bristol |year=1996 |publisher=Robert Hale |page=13-15|location=London |isbn=0709154356|accessdate=2009-03-20 }}</ref> By the 12th century Bristol was an important port, handling much of England's trade with [[Ireland]]. In 1247 a new stone bridge was built, which was replaced by the current [[Bristol Bridge]] in the 1760s,<ref>{{cite web | title=Bristol Bridge | work=Images of England | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=378988 | accessdate=2006-12-22}}</ref> 
and the town was extended to incorporate neighbouring suburbs, becoming in 1373 a [[county corporate|county]] in its own right.<ref name=rayfield>{{cite book |last=Rayfield |first=Jack |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Somerset & Avon |year=1985 |publisher=Cadogan |location=London |isbn=0947754091 }}</ref> During this period Bristol also became a centre of shipbuilding and manufacturing. Bristol was the starting point for many important voyages, notably [[John Cabot]]'s 1497 voyage of exploration to [[North America]].<ref name="croxton">{{cite journal|last=Croxton|first=Derek|date=1990-1991|title=The Cabot Dilemma: John Cabot's 1497 Voyage & the Limits of Historiography|journal=Essays in History|publisher=Corcoran Department of History at the University of Virgini|location=Virginia|volume=Volume Thirty-Three|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/journals/EH/EH33/croxto33.html|accessdate=2009-03-16}}</ref>
[[Image:bristol.cathedral.west.front.arp.jpg|thumb|left|The west front of Bristol Cathedral]]
By the 14th century Bristol was one of England's three largest [[medieval]] towns after London, along with [[York]] and [[Norwich]], with perhaps 15,000<U+2013>20,000 inhabitants on the eve of the [[Black Death]] of 1348<U+2013>49.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lovemytown.co.uk/LocalHistory/LocalHistoryTable1.htm |title=Largest towns in England in 1334 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10 |work=Love my town }}</ref> 
The plague resulted in a prolonged pause in the growth of Bristol's population, with numbers remaining at 10,000&ndash;12,000 through most of the 15th and 16th centuries. The [[Diocese of Bristol]] was founded in 1542,<ref>{{cite web|url=URL: http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=35299|title=BRISTOL: Introduction|last=Horn|first=Joyce M|date=1996|work=Fasti Ecclesiae Anglicanae 1541-1857: volume 8: Bristol, Gloucester, Oxford and Peterborough dioceses|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|pages=3-6|accessdate=2009-03-14}}</ref> 
with the former [[Abbey]] of [[Augustine of Canterbury|St. Augustine]], founded by [[Robert Fitzharding]] in 1140,<ref>{{cite book|last=Bettey|first=Joseph|title=St Augustine's Abbey, Bristol|publisher=Bristol Branch of the Historical Association|location=Bristol|date=1996|pages=1-5|accessdate=2009-03-20}}</ref> becoming [[Bristol Cathedral]]. Traditionally this is equivalent to the town being granted [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]]. During the [[English Civil War|1640s English Civil War]] the city was occupied by [[Cavalier|Royalist]] military, after they overran [[Royal Fort]], the last [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] stronghold in the city.<ref>{{cite web | title= Bristol | work=Fortified Places | url=http://www.fortified-places.com/bristol.html | accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref> 

Renewed growth came with the 17th-century rise of England's [[American colonies]] and the rapid 18th-century expansion of England's part in the [[Atlantic slave trade|Atlantic trade]] in Africans taken for [[slavery]] in the [[Americas]]. Bristol, along with [[Liverpool]], became a centre for the [[Triangular trade]].  In the first stage of this trade manufactured goods were taken to [[West Africa]] and exchanged for Africans who were then, in the second stage or middle passage,  transported across the Atlantic in brutal conditions.<ref name=nmm>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.nmm.ac.uk/freedom/viewTheme.cfm/theme/triangular
|title=Triangular trade
|publisher=National Maritime Museum
|accessdate=2009-03-22
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> The third leg of the triangle brought plantation goods such as sugar, tobacco, rum, rice and cotton<ref name=nmm /> and also a small number of slaves who were sold to the aristocracy as house servants, some eventually buying their freedom.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.17488
|title=Black Lives in England : The Slave Trade and Abolition
|publisher=
|accessdate=2009-03-22
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> During the height of the slave trade, from 1700 to 1807, more than 2,000 slaving ships were fitted out at Bristol, carrying a (conservatively) estimated half a million people from Africa to the Americas and slavery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empiremuseum.co.uk/pdf/pressoffice/press_release_13_12_05.pdf |title=Lottery Fund rejects Bristol application in support of a major exhibition to commemorate the 200th Anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10 |format=PDF |work=British Empire & Commonwealth Museum }}</ref>  
The [[Seven Stars Public House, Bristol|Seven Stars]] [[public house]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brh.org.uk/articles/seven_stars.html |title=Seven Stars, Slavery and Freedom! |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-18 |work=Bristol Radical History Group }}</ref> 
where [[abolitionist]] [[Thomas Clarkson]] collected information on the slave trade still exists.
[[Image:Bristol 1873.png|thumb|An 1873 engraving showing sights around Bristol]]
Fishermen from Bristol had fished the [[Grand Banks]] of [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] since the 15th century<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19950319/ai_n13972306
|title=REAR WINDOW: NEWFOUNDLAND Where fishes swim, men will fight
|publisher=The Independent
|date=19 March 1995
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=Cathcart
|first=Brian
}}
</ref> and began settling Newfoundland permanently in larger numbers in the 17th century establishing colonies at [[Bristol's Hope, Newfoundland and Labrador|Bristol's Hope]] and [[Cuper's Cove, Newfoundland and Labrador|Cuper's Cove]]. Bristol's strong nautical ties meant that maritime safety was an important issue in the city. During the 19th century [[Samuel Plimsoll]], "the sailor's friend", campaigned to make the seas safer; he was shocked by the overloaded cargoes, and successfully fought for a compulsory [[Waterline|load line]] on ships.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2008/05/14/plimsoll_feature.shtml
|title=Samuel Plimsoll - the seaman's friend
|publisher=BBC - Bristol - History
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

Competition from [[Liverpool]] from c.&nbsp;1760, the disruption of maritime commerce caused by wars with [[France]] (1793) and the abolition of the slave trade (1807) contributed to the city's failure to keep pace with the newer manufacturing centres of the [[North of England]] and the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]]. The passage up the heavily [[tidal]] [[Avon Gorge]], which had made the port highly secure during the [[Middle Ages]], had become a liability which the construction of a new "[[Floating Harbour]]" (designed by [[William Jessop (engineer)|William Jessop]]) in 1804&ndash;9 failed to overcome, as the great cost of the scheme led to excessive harbour dues.<ref name="buchanan-cossons">{{cite book|last=Buchanan|first=R A|coauthors=Cossons, Neil|title=The Industrial Archaeology of the Bristol Region|publisher=David & Charles|location=Newton Abbot|date=1969|pages=32-33|chapter=2|accessdate=2009-03-14}}</ref> Nevertheless, Bristol's population (66,000 in 1801) quintupled during the 19th century, supported by new industries and growing commerce.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/GBH_match_page.jsp?ons=Bristol |title=A vision of Bristol UA/City |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-01-29 |work=A Vision of Britain}}</ref> 
It was particularly associated with the [[Victorian era]] [[engineer]] [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]], who designed the [[Great Western Railway]] between Bristol and [[London Paddington]], two pioneering Bristol-built ocean going [[steamship]]s, the [[SS Great Britain]] and [[SS Great Western]], and the [[Clifton Suspension Bridge]]. [[John Wesley]] founded the very first [[Methodist]] Chapel, called the [[New Room, Bristol|New Room]], in Bristol in 1739. [[Bristol Riots|Riots]] occurred in 1793<ref>{{cite book|last=Hunt|first=Henry|title=Memoirs of Henry Hunt, Esq.|publisher=Project Gutenberg|date=original circa 1818|volume=3|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/dirs/etext05/8hnt310.txt|accessdate=2009-03-14}}</ref> and 1831, the first beginning as a protest at renewal of an act levying [[toll (road usage)|toll]]s on Bristol Bridge, and the latter after the rejection of the second [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Bill]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/madeinbristol/2004/04/riot/riot.shtml
|title=BBC - Made in Bristol - 1831 Riot facts
|publisher=www.bbc.co.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>
[[Image:Bristol map 1946.jpg|thumb|left|A map of Bristol from 1946.]]
Bristol's city centre suffered severe damage from [[Luftwaffe]] bombing during the [[Bristol Blitz]] of [[World War II]].<ref>[http://fishponds.org.uk/luftbrim.html John Penny MA; The Luftwaffe over the Bristol area 1940-44]Retrieved: 14 July 2008</ref> The original central shopping area, near the bridge and castle, is now a park containing two bombed out churches and some fragments of the castle. A third bombed church nearby, [[St Nicholas, Bristol|St Nicholas]], has been restored and has been made into a museum which houses a [[triptych]] by [[William Hogarth]], painted for the high altar of [[St Mary Redcliffe]] in 1756. The museum also contains statues moved from [[Arno's Court Triumphal Arch]], of [[Edward I of England|King Edward I]] and [[King Edward III]] taken from Lawfords' Gate of the city walls when they were demolished around 1760, and 13th century figures from Bristol's Newgate representing Robert, the builder of [[Bristol Castle]], and [[Geoffrey de Montbray|Geoffrey de Montbray, Bishop of Coutances]], builder of the fortified walls of the city.<ref>{{cite web | title=Four figures on Arno's Gateway | work=Public Monument and Sculpture Association National Recording Project | url=http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/BL/BR137.htm | accessdate=2007-03-19}}</ref>

The rebuilding of [[Bristol city centre]] was characterised by large, cheap 1960s [[tower block]]s, [[brutalist architecture]] and expansion of roads.  Since the 1980s another trend has emerged with the closure of some main roads, the restoration of the [[Georgian period]] [[Queen Square, Bristol|Queen Square]] and [[Portland Square, Bristol|Portland Square]], the regeneration of the Broadmead shopping area, and the demolition of one of the city centre's tallest post-war blocks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/4608986.stm |title=Demolition of city tower begins |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10 |work=BBC News | date= 13 January 2006}}</ref>
 
The removal of the docks to [[Avonmouth Docks]] and [[Royal Portbury Dock]], {{convert|7|mi|km|1}} downstream from the city centre during the 20th century has also allowed redevelopment of the old central dock area (the "[[Floating Harbour]]") in recent decades, although at one time the continued existence of the docks was in jeopardy as it was viewed as a derelict industrial site rather than an asset. However the holding, in 1996, of the first [[International Festival of the Sea, 1996|International Festival of the Sea]] in and around the docks, affirmed the dockside area in its new leisure role as a key feature of the city.<ref>{{cite book |authorlink= |coauthors=|title=Bristol's Harbourside: A Guide to the City Docks |year=1997 |publisher=Hotwell Press |location=Bristol |isbn=0-9530270-0-7 |author=Jeremy McNeill ; illustrations by Ben Wookey. }}</ref>

==Economy and industry==
{{main|Economy and industry of Bristol}}
[[Image:BristolTheNails.jpg|thumb|right|The Nails in Corn Street, over which trading deals were made]]
As a major seaport, Bristol has a long history of trading commodities, originally wool cloth exports and imports of fish, wine, grain and dairy produce,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=108165
|title=Chapter 3 - Murage, keyage and pavage 
|publisher=British History Online
|accessdate=2009-03-20
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> later [[tobacco]], tropical fruits and plantation goods; major imports now are motor vehicles, grain, timber, fresh produce and petroleum products. Deals were originally struck on a personal basis in the former trading area around Corn Street, and in particular, over bronze trading tables, known as "[[The Exchange, Bristol#The Nails|The Nails]]". This is often given as the origin of the expression "cash on the nail", meaning immediate payment, however it is likely that the expression was in use before the ''nails'' were erected.<ref>{{cite book|last=Knowles|first=Elizabeth|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Phrase and Fable|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=2006|isbn=0198602197|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-02-05}}</ref>

As well as Bristol's nautical connections, the city's economy is reliant on the [[aerospace]] industry, defence, the media, information technology and financial services sectors, and tourism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Tourism-Travel/bristol-today-an-overview-of-the-city.en?page=2#internalSection2 |title=Bristol Today - a thriving economy|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-03-14 |work=Bristol City Council }}</ref> The former [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD)'s Procurement Executive, later the [[Defence Procurement Agency]], and now [[Defence Equipment & Support]], moved to a purpose-built headquarters at Abbey Wood, Filton in 1995. The site employs some 7,000 to 8,000 staff and is responsible for procuring and supporting much of the MoD's defence equipment.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/History/HistoryOfTheMOD/
|title=History of the MOD
|publisher=MoD
|accessdate=2009-03-25
|last=
|first=}}</ref> 

In 2004 Bristol's [[GDP]] was <U+00A3>9.439&nbsp;billion, and the combined GDP of Gloucestershire, Wiltshire and North Somerset was <U+00A3>44.098&nbsp;billion.  The GDP per head was <U+00A3>23,962 (US$47,738, <U+20AC>35,124) making the city more affluent than the UK as a whole, at 40% above the national average. This makes it the third-highest per-capita GDP of any [[England|English]] city, after [[London]] and [[Nottingham]], and the fifth highest GDP per capita of any city in the United Kingdom, behind London, [[Edinburgh]], [[Glasgow]], [[Belfast]] and Nottingham.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/regional_snapshot_2006/SubregionalGVA.xls |title= Sub-regional: Gross value added1 (GVA) at current basic price}}</ref> In March 2007, Bristol's [[unemployment]] rate was 4.8%, compared with 4.0% for the south west and 5.5% for England.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=276834&c=BS8+4NQ&d=13&e=4&g=398722&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1237069317892&enc=1
|title=Lead Key Figures
|publisher=Office for National Statistics
|accessdate=2009-03-14
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

Although Bristol's economy is no longer reliant upon the [[Port of Bristol]], which was relocated gradually to the mouth of the Avon to new docks at Avonmouth (1870s)<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42297
|title=Gloucester, 1835-1985 - Economic development to 1914 | British History Online
|publisher=www.british-history.ac.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-20
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and Royal Portbury Dock (1977) as the size of shipping increased, the city is the largest importer of cars to the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.office-connection.com/advice/bristol-business-statistics/
|title=Bristol Business Statistics <U+00BB> Expert Office Advice
|publisher=www.office-connection.com
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> Since the port was leased in 1991, <U+00A3>330&nbsp;million has been invested and the annual tonnage throughput has increased from 3.9 million long tons (4 million metric tonnes) to 11.8 million long tons (12 million metric tonnes).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristolport.co.uk/about |title=About |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-03-14 |work=The Bristol Port Company

}}</ref> The tobacco trade and cigarette manufacturing have now ceased, but imports of wines and spirits by [[John Harvey & Sons|Harveys]] and Averys continue. 

The financial services sector employs 59,000 in the city,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.investwest.org/financial.shtml
|title=Invest West - the West of England Financial & Business Services Sector
|publisher=www.investwest.org
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and the [[High technology|high-tech]] sector is important, with 50 micro-electronics and silicon design companies, which employ around 5,000 people, including the [[Hewlett-Packard]] national research laboratories, which opened in 1983.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.siliconsouthwest.co.uk/index.php?page=portfolio&dept=rsd_dept&subpage=view_portfolio&portfolio_id=1
|title=About the Region
|publisher=Silicon Southwest
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> 
<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.hpl.hp.com/bristol/
|title=HP Lab, Bristol, UK
|publisher=Hewlet Packard
|accessdate=2009-03-22
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> 
Bristol is the UK's seventh most popular destination for foreign tourists, and the city receives nine million visitors each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Tourism-Travel/bristol-today-an-overview-of-the-city.en |title=Bristol Today - an overview of the city |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-03-10 |work=Bristol City Council }}</ref>

In the 20th century, Bristol's manufacturing activities expanded to include aircraft production at [[Filton]], by the [[Bristol Aeroplane Company]], and aero-engine manufacture by [[Bristol Aero Engines]] (later [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]]) at [[Patchway]]. The aeroplane company became famous for the [[World War I]] [[Bristol F.2 Fighter|Bristol Fighter]],<ref name="BOYNE">{{cite book|last=Boyne|first=Walter J|title=Air Warfare|publisher=ABC-Clio|date=1 July  2002|pages=105|isbn=1576073459|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=FW_50wm8VnMC&pg=PA105&lpg=PA105&dq=famous+bristol+planes&source=bl&ots=SfcPo0zjYU&sig=_EXbInDZkREunbEYGb7FZmPFkAQ&hl=en&ei=kTm9SanPFsPgtgel5rj3Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=3&ct=result#PPA105,M1|accessdate=2009-03-15}}</ref> and [[World War II|Second World War]] [[Bristol Blenheim|Blenheim]] and [[Beaufighter]] aircraft.<ref name="BOYNE" /> In the 1950s it became one of the country's major manufacturers of civil aircraft, with the [[Bristol Freighter]] and [[Bristol Britannia|Britannia]] and the huge [[Bristol Brabazon|Brabazon]] airliner. The [[Bristol Aeroplane Company]] diversified into car manufacturing in the 1940s, producing hand-built [[luxury car]]s at their factory in [[Filton]], under the name [[Bristol Cars]], which became independent from the Bristol Aeroplane Company in 1960.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.boc.net/history.html | work= Bristol Owners Club | title= A brief history of the Bristol Marque | accessdate= 2007-08-29}} </ref>  The city also gave its name to the Bristol make of buses, manufactured in the city from 1908 to 1983, first by the local bus operating company, [[Bristol Omnibus Company|Bristol Tramways]], and from 1955 by [[Bristol Commercial Vehicles]].

[[Image:Concorde on Bristol.jpg|thumb|left|The last ever flight of any [[Concorde]], 26 November 2003. The aircraft is seen a few minutes before landing on the [[Filton]] runway from which it first flew in 1969.]]
In the 1960s Filton played a key role in the Anglo-French ''[[Concorde]]'' supersonic airliner project. The Bristol Aeroplane Compny became part of the British partner, the [[British Aircraft Corporation]] (BAC). Concorde components were manufactured in British and French factories and shipped to the two final assembly plants, in [[Toulouse]] and Filton.  The French manufactured the centre fuselage and centre wing and the British the nose, rear fuselage, fin and wingtips, while the [[Rolls-Royce Olympus|Olympus 593]] engine's manufacture was split between [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] (Filton) and [[SNECMA]] ([[Paris]]). The British Concorde prototype made its maiden flight from Filton to [[RAF Fairford]] on 9 April 1969, five weeks after the French test flight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concordesst.com/history/earlyindex.html |title=Concorde Early History |work=concordesst.com |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref>
In 2003 [[British Airways]] and [[Air France]] decided to cease flying the aircraft and to retire them to locations (mostly museums) around the world. On 26&nbsp;November 2003 Concorde 216 made the final Concorde flight, returning to Filton airfield to be kept there permanently as the centrepiece of a projected air museum. This museum will include the existing Bristol Aero Collection, which includes a [[Bristol Britannia]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concordeatfilton.org.uk/ |title=Concorde at Filton |work=BAC Trading Ltd |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref>

The aerospace industry remains a major segment of the local economy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epolitix.com/mpwebsites/mpwebsitepage/mpsite/dr-doug-naysmith/mppage/constituency-5/ |title=Dr Doug Naysmith - Bristol Northwest |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-03-14 | work=ePolitix.com }}</ref>  
The major aerospace companies in Bristol now are [[BAE Systems]], (formed by merger between [[Marconi Electronic Systems]] and [[BAe]]; the latter being formed by a merger of BAC, Hawker Siddeley and Scottish Aviation), [[Airbus]]<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.airbus.com/en/worldwide/airbus_in_uk.html
|title=Airbus in UK
|publisher=www.airbus.com
|accessdate=2009-03-20
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and Rolls-Royce, all based at Filton, and aerospace engineering is a prominent research area at the nearby [[University of the West of England]]. Another important [[aviation]] company in the city is [[Cameron Balloons]], who manufacture [[hot air balloon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2008/07/14/fiesta_how_do_you_make_a_balloon_feature.shtml |title=Balloon Fiesta: How to make a hot-air balloon|work=BBC Bristol|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-31 }}</ref> Each August the city is host to the [[Bristol International Balloon Fiesta]], one of Europe's largest hot air balloon events.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2008/07/28/fiesta_don_cameron_feature.shtml
|title=BBC - Bristol - Balloon Fiesta - Balloon Fiesta: Don Cameron
|publisher=www.bbc.co.uk
|dateformat=dmy
|accessdate=2009-02-05
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

A new  <U+00A3>500 million shopping centre called [[Cabot Circus]] opened in 2008 amidst claims from developers and politicians that Bristol would become one of England's top ten retail destinations.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Cabot-Circus-puts-belong/article-354732-detail/article.html
|title=Bristol shopping centre Cabot Circus will lift city into top 10 say business leaders
|publisher=www.thisisbristol.co.uk
|dateformat=dmy
|accessdate=2009-02-05
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> Bristol was selected as one of the world's top ten cities for 2009 by international travel publishers [[Dorling Kindersley]] in their ''[[Eyewitness Books|Eyewitness]]'' series of guides for young adults.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.travelpulse.com/Resources/Editorial.aspx?n=50049
|title=Destination - Bristol Placed in Top 10 for Eyewitness Guides
|publisher=www.travelpulse.com|date=December 29 2008|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2009-02-05
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> The city was also listed as top of the [[Sustainable city|Sustainable Cities]] Index 2008 by environmental charity [[Forum for the Future]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.forumforthefuture.org/blog/sustainable-cities08-update
