===Arts===
[[Image:Bristol Old Vic (750px).jpg|thumb|The Coopers Hall, entrance to the Bristol Old Vic Theatre Royal complex]]
[[Image:Bristol pw from ms.jpg|thumb|[[Bristol Industrial Museum]].]]
[[Image:llandoger.trow.overall.arp.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Llandoger Trow]], an ancient public house in the heart of Bristol.]]
The city is famous for its music and film industries, and was a finalist for the 2008 [[European Capital of Culture]], but did not win.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/2877.aspx
|title=Six Cities Make Short List For European Capital Of Culture 2008
|publisher=www.culture.gov.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-22
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

The city's principal theatre company, the [[Bristol Old Vic]], was founded in 1946 as an offshoot of the [[Old Vic]] company in London. Its premises on [[King Street, Bristol|King Street]] consist of the 1766 Theatre Royal (400 seats), a modern studio theatre called the New Vic (150 seats), and foyer and bar areas in the adjacent [[Coopers' Hall]] (built 1743). The Theatre Royal is a grade I [[listed building]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=379885|title=The Theatre Royal |work=Images of England|publisher=English Heritage|accessdate=2009-03-16}}</ref><ref name=gradei>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/cms-service/stream/asset/;jsessionid=4F42388454C5F5D3A5CA2E3AF5F560AA.tcwwwaplaws3?asset_id=20848045
|title=Grade I Listed Buildings in Bristol
|publisher=Bristol City Council
|format=PDF
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and is the oldest continuously operating theatre in England.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20050327/ai_n13483838
|title=England special: In the footsteps of Bristol's slave traders
|publisher=The Independent on Sunday
|date=27 March 2005
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=Rowe
|first=Mark
}}
</ref> The [[Bristol Old Vic Theatre School]], which had originated in King Street is now a separate company. The [[Bristol Hippodrome]] is a larger theatre (1981 seats) which hosts national touring productions. Other theatres include the [[Tobacco Factory]] (250 seats), [[Queen Elizabeth's Hospital|QEH]] (220 seats), the Redgrave Theatre (at [[Clifton College]]) (320 seats) and the Alma Tavern (50 seats). Bristol's theatre scene includes a large variety of producing theatre companies, apart from the Bristol Old Vic company, including [[Show of Strength Theatre Company]], Shakespeare at the Tobacco Factory and Travelling Light Theatre Company. Theatre Bristol is a partnership between Bristol City Council, [[Arts Council England]] and local theatre practitioners which aims to develop the theatre industry in Bristol.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theatrebristol.net/about | title= About Us | publisher= Theatre Bristol | accessdate=2008-05-08}}</ref>
There are also a number of organisations within the city which act to support theatre makers, for example [[Equity (trade union)|Equity]], the actors union, has a General Branch based in the city,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.equity.org.uk/branches/?branchid=37 | title=Bristol and West General Branch | publisher= Equity | accessdate=2008-05-08}}</ref> and Residence which provides office, social and rehearsal space for several Bristol-based theatre and performance companies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.residence.org.uk/node/34 | title= About | publisher= Residence | accessdate=2008-05-08}}</ref>

Since the late 1970s, the city has been home to bands combining punk, funk, [[Dub music|dub]] and [[political consciousness]], amongst the most notable have been [[The Pop Group]]<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:f9fexq85ldte
|title=The Pop Group > Overview
|publisher=www.allmusic.com
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=Dougan
|first=John
}}
</ref> and [[trip hop]] or "Bristol Sound" artists such as [[Tricky]],<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:kzfyxqqgldde
|title=Tricky > Overview
|publisher=www.allmusic.com
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=Erlewine
|first=Stephen Thomas
}}
</ref> [[Portishead]]<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:gxfwxqr5ldje~T1
|title=Portishead > Biography
|publisher=www.allmusic.com
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=Erlewine
|first=Stephen Thomas
}}
</ref> and [[Massive Attack]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:j9fwxqw5ldse~T1
|title=Massive Attack > Biography
