}}
</ref> This music is part of the wider Bristol urban culture scene which received international media attention in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web | title=Blagging and Boasting | work=Metroactive Music | url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/metro/06.18.98/bristol-9824.html | accessdate=2007-01-28}}</ref> 
Bristol has many live music venues, the largest of which is the 2,000-seat [[Colston Hall]], named after [[Edward Colston]]. Others include the [[O2 Academy Bristol|Bristol Academy]], Fiddlers, [[The Victoria Rooms|Victoria Rooms]], [[Trinity Centre]], [[St George's Church, Brandon Hill|St George's Bristol]] and a range of public houses from the jazz-orientated [[The Old Duke]] to rock at the Fleece and Firkin and indie bands at the Louisiana.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/student/article2097881.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2
|title=A student's guide to...University of Bristol - Times Online
