===Architecture===
{{main|Buildings and architecture of Bristol}}

Bristol has 51 [[Grade I listed buildings in Bristol|Grade I listed buildings]],<ref name=gradei /> 500  [[Grade II* listed buildings in Bristol|Grade II*]] and over 3,800 [[Grade II listed buildings in Bristol|Grade II]] buildings,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Leisure-Culture/Conservation/listed-buildings/listed-buildings.en
|title=Bristol City Council: Listed buildings register: Listed buildings
|publisher=www.bristol.gov.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> in a wide variety of [[Architectural|architectural]] styles, ranging from the [[Medieval architecture|medieval]] to the 21st century. In the mid-19th century, [[Bristol Byzantine]], an architectural style unique to the city, was developed, of which several examples have survived. Buildings from most of the [[History of architecture|architectural periods]] of the United Kingdom can be seen throughout the city. Surviving elements of the fortified city and castle date back to the medieval era,<ref name="burrough">{{cite book |last=Burrough |first=THB |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Bristol |year=1970 |publisher=Studio Vista |location=London |isbn=0289798043 }}</ref> also some churches dating from the 12th century onwards.<ref>{{cite web | title=Church of St James | work=Images of England | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=380890 | accessdate=2009-03-15}}</ref> 

Outside the historical city centre there are several large [[Tudor period|Tudor]] mansions built for wealthy merchants.<ref>{{cite web | title=Red Lodge and attached rubble walls and entrance steps  | work=Images of England | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=380113 | accessdate=2007-03-10}}</ref> [[Almshouses]]<ref>{{cite web | title=St Nicholas' Almshouses, Nos.1-10 | work=Images of England | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=379882 | accessdate=2007-02-21}}</ref> and [[public houses]] of the same period still exist,<ref>{{cite web | title=Llandoger Trow | work=Images of England | url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?id=379857 | accessdate=2007-02-22}}</ref>  intermingled with modern development. Several [[Georgian architecture|Georgian-era]] squares were laid out for the enjoyment of the [[middle class]] as prosperity increased in the 18th century.<ref>Andrew Foyle, ''Bristol'', Pevsner Architectural Guides (2004) ISBN 0-300-10442-1</ref>

During [[World War II]], the [[Bristol city centre|city centre]] suffered from extensive bombing during the [[Bristol Blitz]].<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20070322080553/http://weldgen.tripod.com/bristol-history/id6.html Pictoral history of Bristol], bristolhistory.com. Retrieved [[2006-04-14]].</ref> The redevelopment of shopping centres, office buildings, and the harbourside continues apace.

===Sport and leisure===
[[Image:Ashton Gate & Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ashton Gate stadium]] with the [[Clifton Suspension Bridge]] in the background over the [[Avon Gorge]]]]
The city has two [[The Football League|League]] [[Football (soccer)|football]] clubs: [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]], as well as a [[Football_teams_in_Bristol#Sport|number of non-league]] clubs. Bristol City was formed in 1897 a became runners-up in Division One in 1907, and losing FA Cup finalists in 1909.  They returned to the top flight in 1976, but in 1980 started a descent to Division Four. They were promoted to the second tier of English football in 2007. The team lost in the play-off final of the Championship to [[Hull City]] (2007/2008 season). City announced plans for a new 30,000 all-seater stadium to replace their home, Ashton Gate.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/Records/0,,10327~63412,00.html
|title=POTTED HISTORY
|publisher=Bristol City FC
|date=6 June 2008
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] is the oldest professional football team in Bristol, formed in 1883.  They are just below mid-table in League One, and reached the quarter-final stage of the [[FA Cup]].  During their history, Rovers have been champions of the [[League One|(old) division Three]] (1952/53, 1989/90), [[Watney Cup]] Winners (1972, 2006/07), and runners-up in the [[Football League Trophy|Johnstone's Paint Trophy]]. The Club have planning permission to re-develop the [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]] into an 18,500 all-seat Stadium to be completed by December 2010.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.football-england.com/Bristol_Rovers_Football_Club_FC_Pirates_BRFC.html
|title=Bristol Rovers Football Club FC Pirates BRFC
|publisher=www.football-england.com
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

[[Image:Gloucestershire County Cricket Ground.jpg|thumb|left|The County Ground, [[Ashley Down]]]]
The city is also home to [[Bristol Rugby]] [[rugby union]] club,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bristolrugby.co.uk/history.php
|title=Bristol Rugby : History Page
|publisher=www.bristolrugby.co.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> a [[First-class cricket|first-class]] [[cricket]] side, [[Gloucestershire C.C.C.]]<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.gloscricket.co.uk/
|title=Gloucestershire County Cricket Club
|publisher=www.gloscricket.co.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and a [[Rugby League Conference]] side, the [[Bristol Sonics]].  The city also stages an annual [[Bristol Half Marathon|half marathon]], and in 2001 played host to the [[2001 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships|World Half Marathon Championships]].  There are several athletics clubs in Bristol, including Bristol and West AC, Bitton Road Runners and Westbury Harriers.  Speedway racing was staged, with breaks, at the Knowle Stadium from 1928 to 1960, when it was closed and the site redeveloped. The sport briefly returned to the city in the 1970s when the Bulldogs raced at [[Eastville Stadium]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Bamford | first = Roger | title = Bristol Bulldogs Speedway : Bristol Bulldogs Speedway | publisher = NPI Media Group| date = 2003-9-30 | page = 128 | url = http://www.thehistorypress.co.uk/Default.aspx?tabid=7613&ProductID=3680 | isbn = 978-0752428659}}</ref>

The [[Bristol International Balloon Fiesta]], a major event for [[Hot air balloon|hot-air ballooning]] in the UK, is held each summer in the grounds of [[Ashton Court]], to the west of the city.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2008/03/20/balloon_fiesta2008_feature.shtml
|title=Balloon Fiesta celebrates 30 years
|publisher=BBC Bristol
|date=14 April 2008
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> The fiesta draws substantial crowds even for the early morning lift beginning at about 6.30&nbsp;am. Events and a fairground entertain visitors during the day. A second mass ascent is made in the early evening, again taking advantage of lower wind speeds. Until 2007 Ashton Court also played host to the [[Ashton Court festival]] each summer, an outdoor music festival known as the Bristol Community Festival.

===Media===
[[Image:Bristol International Balloon Fiesta.JPG|thumb|[[Bristol International Balloon Fiesta]]]]
Bristol has two daily newspapers, the ''[[Western Daily Press]]'' and the ''[[Bristol Evening Post]]''; a weekly free newspaper, the ''[[Bristol Observer]]''; and a Bristol edition of the free [[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|''Metro'']] newspaper, all owned by the [[Daily Mail and General Trust]].<ref>
