</ref> The city has several local radio stations, including [[BBC Radio Bristol]], [[Bristol's GWR FM|GWR FM]] (previously known as Radio West), [[Brunel Classic Gold|Classic Gold 1260]], [[Kiss 101]], [[Star 107.2]], [[BCFM|BCfm]] (a community radio station launched March 2007), [[Ujima 98 FM]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themk1boy.co.uk/radio/|title=Ujima 98 FM|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-23}}</ref> [[Original 106.5]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Original 106.5fm Bristol | work=Original 106.5fm | url=http://www.originalbristol.com/ | accessdate=2009-03-14}}</ref> 
as well as two student radio stations, [[The Hub (radio station)|The Hub]] and [[BURST]]. Bristol also boasts television productions such as ''[[The West Tonight]]'' for [[ITV West]] (formerly HTV West), ''[[Points West]]'' for [[BBC West]], hospital drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' and Endemol productions such as ''[[Deal or no deal|Deal Or No Deal]]''. Bristol has been used as a location for the Channel 4 comedy drama ''[[Teachers (UK TV series)|Teachers]]'', teen drama ''[[Skins (TV series)|Skins]]'' and horror-drama series ''[[Being Human (TV series)|Being Human]]''.

===Dialect===
A dialect of [[English language|English]] is spoken by some Bristol inhabitants, known colloquially as ''Bristolian'', or even more colloquially as "Bristle" or "Brizzle". Bristol is the only large English city with a [[Rhotic and non-rhotic accents|rhotic accent]], in which the ''r'' in words like ''car'' is pronounced. The unusual feature of this dialect, unique to Bristol, is the ''Bristol L'' (or ''terminal L''), in which an ''L'' sound is appended to words that end in an 'a' or 'o'.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stoke |first=Harry |authorlink= |coauthors=Vinny Green |title=A Dictionary of Bristle |year=2003 |publisher=Broadcast Books |location=Bristol |isbn=1874092656 }}</ref> 
Thus "area" becomes "areal", etc. Further Bristolian linguistic features are the addition of a superfluous "to" in questions relating to direction or orientation (a feature also common to the coastal towns of [[South Wales]]), or using "to" instead of "at"; and using male [[pronouns]] "he", "him" instead of "it". For example, "Where's that?" would be phrased as "Where's he to?", a structure exported to [[Newfoundland English]].<ref>{{cite web | title=An Introduction to Newfoundland Vernacular English | work=Language Variation in Canada | url=http://www.unh.edu/linguistics/courses/790CS/final.papers/NF.English.paper.htm | accessdate=2007-01-28}}</ref>

[[Image:Cabot Tower (600px).jpg|thumb|[[Cabot Tower (Bristol)|Cabot Tower]] viewed from Brandon Hill park.]]
Stanley Ellis, a dialect researcher, found that many of the dialect words in the Filton area were linked to work in the aerospace industry.  He described this as "a cranky, crazy, crab-apple tree of language and with the sharpest, juiciest flavour that I've heard for a long time".<ref>Simon Elmes, "Talking for Britain", p.39</ref>

==Politics and government==
[[Image:Bristol council house.jpg|thumb|The [[Council House, Bristol|Council House]], the seat of local government]]
{{main|Politics of Bristol}}
[[Image:Bristol-St Mary Redcliffe-Docks.jpg|thumb|right|[[St Mary Redcliffe]] church and the [[Floating Harbour]], Bristol.]]
Bristol City Council consists of 70 councillors representing 35 wards. They are elected in thirds with two councillors per ward, each serving a four-year term. Wards never have both councillors up for election at the same time, so effectively two-thirds of the wards are up each election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Council-Democracy/Democracy-Elections/future-elections.en |title= Wards up for future elections|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Bristol City Council }}</ref> 
The Council has long been dominated by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], but recently the [[Liberal Democrats]] have grown strong in the city and as the largest party took minority control of the Council at the 2005 election. In 2007, Labour and the Conservatives joined forces to vote down the Liberal Democrat administration, and as a result, Labour ruled the council under a minority administration, with Helen Holland as the council leader.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/6682343.stm |title=Council leader battle resolved |date=2007-05-27|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-31 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>
In February 2009, the Labour group resigned, and the Liberal Democrats took office with their own minority administration.<ref>
{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/7910368.stm
|title=Labour 'lost council confidence'
|publisher=BBC News Bristol
|date=February 25, 2009
|accessdate=2009-02-25
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> The Lord Mayor is [[Liberal Democrats|Lib Dem]] Councillor Chris Davis.<ref>{{Citation|title=Councillor Chris Davis|url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Council-Democracy/Elected-Representatives/lord-mayor-of-bristol.en|publisher=[[Bristol City Council]]}}</ref>

Bristol constituencies in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] cross the borders with neighbouring authorities, and the city is divided into Bristol [[Bristol West (UK Parliament constituency)|West]], [[Bristol East (UK Parliament constituency)|East]], [[Bristol South (UK Parliament constituency)|South]] and [[Bristol North West (UK Parliament constituency)|North-west]] and [[Kingswood (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingswood]]. [[Northavon (UK Parliament constituency)|Northavon]] also covers some of the suburbs, but none of the administrative county. At the next General Election, the boundaries will be changed to coincide with the county boundary. Kingswood will no longer cover any of the county, and a new [[Filton and Bradley Stoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Filton and Bradley Stoke]] constituency will include the suburbs in South Gloucestershire. There are four [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] and one Liberal Democrat [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Council-Democracy/Elected-Representatives/bristols-members-of-parliament-and-mep-listings.en |title=Bristol's Members of Parliament and Members of the European Parliament |accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Bristol City Council | year= 2005 }}</ref>

Bristol has a tradition of local political activism, and has been home to many important political figures. [[Tony Benn]], a veteran left-wing politician, was Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Bristol South East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol South East]] from 1950 until 1983. [[Edmund Burke]], MP for the [[Bristol (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol constituency]] for six years from 1774, famously insisted that he was a Member of Parliament first, rather than a representative of his constituents' interests. In 1963, there was a boycott of the city's buses after the Bristol Omnibus Co. refused to employ black drivers and conductors. The boycott is known to have influenced the creation of the UK's [[Race Relations Act 1965|Race Relations Act]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2005/nov/10/race.immigrationpolicy |title=In praise of... the Race Relations Acts |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |author=Alan Rusbridger |authorlink=Alan Rusbridger |coauthors= |date=2005-11-10 |publisher=Guardian |pages=  |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref> 
The women's rights campaigner [[Emmeline Pethick-Lawrence]] (1867<U+2013>1954) was born in Bristol. The city was the scene of the first of the 1980s riots. In St. Paul's, a number of largely African-Caribbean people rose up against racism, police harassment and mounting dissatisfaction with their social and economic circumstances before similar disturbances followed across the UK. Local support of [[fair trade]] issues was recognised in 2005 when Bristol was granted [[Fairtrade City]] status.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2005/mar/04/fairtrade.ethicalliving
|title=From slave trade to fair trade, Bristol's new image | Environment | The Guardian
|publisher=guardian.co.uk
|date=4 March 2005
|accessdate=2009-03-14
|last=Morris
|first=Steven
}}
</ref>

Bristol is unusual in having been a city with county status since medieval times. The county was expanded to include suburbs such as [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] in 1835, and it was named a [[county borough]] in 1889, when the term was first introduced.<ref name=rayfield/> However, on 1 April 1974, it became a local government district of the short-lived county of [[Avon county|Avon]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1971/nov/16/local-government-bill#S5CV0826P0_19711116_HOC_316
|title=LOCAL GOVERNMENT BILL (Hansard, 16 November 1971)
|publisher=hansard.millbanksystems.com
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> On 1 April 1996, it regained its independence and county status, when the county of Avon was abolished and Bristol became a [[Unitary Authority]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si1995/Uksi_19950493_en_10.htm
|title=The Avon (Structural Change) Order 1995
|publisher=www.opsi.gov.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

==Demographics==

In 2008 the [[Office for National Statistics]] estimated the Bristol unitary authority's population at 416,900,<ref>url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_population/Mid_2007_UK_England_&_Wales_Scotland_and_Northern_Ireland%20_21_08_08.zip[[/url]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/CCI/nugget.asp?ID=6 |title=National Statistics Online |publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-02-27}}</ref> making it the [[List of ceremonial counties of England by population|47th-largest]] ceremonial county in England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=9090&More=Y |title=ONS 2005 Mid-Year Estimates | date= 20 December 2005 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Office of National Statistics }}</ref> 
Using [[United Kingdom Census 2001|Census 2001]] data the ONS estimated the population of the city to be 441,556,<ref name="UrbanPop">{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&Pos=2&ColRank=1&Rank=224 |title=Usual resident population | date= 5 August 2004 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Office for National Statistics, Census 2001 }}</ref> 
and that of the contiguous urban area to be 551,066.<ref name = "ANameSoThatWeDontHaveToUseIbidForTheNextRef">{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/fom2005/03_FOPM_UrbanAreas.pdf |title=The UKs major urban areas |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |format=PDF |work=Office for National Statistics, 2001 }}</ref> 
This makes the city England's sixth most populous city, and ninth most populous urban area.<ref name="ANameSoThatWeDontHaveToUseIbidForTheNextRef"/> 
At {{convert|3599|PD/sqkm|0|lk=on}} it has the seventh-highest population density of any English district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=9395&More=Y |title=ONS 2005 Mid-Year Estimates | date= 10 October 2006 | accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Office of National Statistics }}</ref>

According to 2006 estimates, 88.8% of the population were described as white, 4.2% as Asian or Asian British, 2.9% as black or black British, 2.2% as mixed race, 1.3% as Chinese and 0.7% other. National averages for England were 88.7%, 5.5%, 2.8%, 1.6%, 0.7% and 0.7% for the same groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do;jsessionid=ac1f930bce6d4523a551c994076b0afd590fc57b0fd?a=1&b=276834&c=bristol&d=13&e=13&g=398712&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1227235566109&enc=1&dsFamilyId=1812&nsjs=true&nsck=false&nssvg=false&nswid=1436 |title=Resident Population Estimates by Ethnic Group |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-02-22 | year=2006 |work=Office for National Statistics, 2006 }}</ref> 
===Religion===
In the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], 60% of Bristol's population reported themselves as being [[Christian]], and 25% stated they were not religious; the national UK averages are 72% and 15% respectively. [[Islam]] accounts for 2% of the population (3% nationally), with no other religion above one percent, although 9% did not respond to the question.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=6563&More=Y |title= Key Statistics 07: Religion|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 | date=13 February 2003 |work=Office for National Statistics, Census 2001 }}</ref>

The city has many [[Churches in Bristol|Christian churches]], the most notable being the [[Anglican]] [[Bristol Cathedral]] and [[St. Mary Redcliffe]] and the [[Roman Catholic]] [[Clifton Cathedral]]. [[Nonconformism|Nonconformist chapels]] include [[Buckingham Baptist Chapel]] and [[John Wesley]]'s New Room in Broadmead.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.newroombristol.org.uk/
|title=The New Room Bristol - John Wesley's Chapel in the Horsefair
|publisher=www.newroombristol.org.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> 

The Muslim community is served by three mosques.<ref>
