==Education, science and technology==
[[Image:Victoria Rooms (750px).jpg|thumb|The [[Victoria Rooms (Bristol)|Victoria Rooms]], owned by the [[University of Bristol|University]]]]
{{main|Education in Bristol}}
[[Image:Wills Memorial Building from road during day.jpg|thumb|upright|The University of Bristol's [[Wills Memorial Building]] - a familiar landmark at the top of Park Street]]
Bristol is home to two major institutions of higher education: the [[University of Bristol]], a "[[Red Brick universities|redbrick]]" chartered in 1909, and the [[University of the West of England]], formerly Bristol Polytechnic, which gained university status in 1992. The city also has two dedicated [[further education]] institutions, [[City of Bristol College]] and [[Filton College]], and three [[Theology|theological]] colleges, [[Trinity College, Bristol|Trinity College]], [[Wesley College, Bristol|Wesley College]] and [[Bristol Baptist College]]. The city has 129 infant, junior and primary schools,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol-cyps.org.uk/schools/contacts/school_list_primary.html |title=List of primary schools in Bristol |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2006-04-13 |work=Bristol LEA }}</ref> 
17 secondary schools,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol-cyps.org.uk/schools/contacts/school_list_secondary.html |title=List of secondary schools in Bristol |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2006-04-13 |work=Bristol LEA }}</ref> 
and three city learning centres. It has the country's second highest concentration of [[Independent school (UK)|independent school]] places, after an exclusive corner of north London.<ref name="curtis">{{cite news |first=Curtis |last=Polly |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=To have and have not |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2008/jan/29/publicschools.schools |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher= |date=2008-01-29 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-01-29 }}</ref> The independent schools in the city include [[Colston's School]], [[Clifton College]], [[Clifton High School (Bristol)|Clifton High School]], [[Badminton School]], [[Bristol Cathedral School]], [[Bristol Grammar School]], [[Redland High School]], [[Queen Elizabeth's Hospital]] (the only all-boys school) and [[Red Maids' School]], which claims to be the oldest girls' school in England, having been founded in 1634 by John Whitson.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.redmaids.bristol.sch.uk/page/view/id/1/base/1/
|title=Bristol Independent Girls' Schools
|publisher=Redmaids' School
|accessdate=2009-03-15
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

In 2005, the then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] recognised Bristol's ties to science and technology by naming it one of six "science cities", and promising funding for further development of science in the city,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/university/vc/science-city.html |title=Vice-Chancellor's speeches and articles |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-06 |work=[[University of Bristol]] | date= 11 November 2005 }}</ref> 
with a <U+00A3>300 million science park planned at [[Emerson's Green]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/4925556.stm |title=City science park partner named |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-06 |work=[[BBC News]] | date= 20 April 2006 }}</ref>  
As well as research at the two universities and [[Southmead Hospital]], science education is important in the city, with [[At-Bristol]], [[Bristol Zoo]], [[Bristol Festival of Nature]] and the [[Create Centre]] being prominent local institutions involved in science communication.  The city has a history of scientific luminaries, including the 19th-century chemist Sir [[Humphry Davy]],<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/davy_humphrey.shtml
|title=Sir Humphry Davy (1778 - 1829)
|publisher=www.bbc.co.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> who worked in [[Hotwells]]. [[Bishopston, Bristol|Bishopston]] gave the world [[Nobel Prize]] winning physicist [[Paul Dirac]]<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Dirac.html
|title=Dirac biography
|publisher=www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> for crucial contributions to [[quantum mechanics]] in 1933. [[Cecil Frank Powell]] was Melvill Wills Professor of Physics at Bristol University when he was awarded the Nobel prize for a photographic method of studying nuclear processes and associated discoveries in 1950. The city was birth place of [[Colin Pillinger]],<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://colinpillinger.com/barnstormpr.co.uk/biography.htm
|title=barnstormpr - The website of Professor Colin Pillinger, CBE FRS
|publisher=colinpillinger.com
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> planetary scientist behind the [[Beagle 2]] [[Mars (planet)|Mars]] lander project, and is home to the psychologist [[Richard Gregory]].<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.richardgregory.org/
|title=Professor Richard Gregory on-line
|publisher=www.richardgregory.org
|accessdate=2009-03-07
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

Initiatives such as the [[Flying Start Challenge]] help encourage secondary school pupils around the Bristol area to take an interest in Science and Engineering. Links with major aerospace companies promote technical disciplines and advance students' understanding of practical design.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.flyingstartchallenge.co.uk/
|title=Flying Start Challenge
|publisher=www.flyingstartchallenge.co.uk
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>

==Transport==
{{main|Transport in Bristol}}

Bristol has two principal [[railway station]]s; [[Bristol Parkway railway station|Bristol Parkway]] is located to the north of the city and [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol Temple Meads]] is in the centre. Both offer direct services to many UK destinations. Principal operators are [[First Great Western]] and [[CrossCountry]]. There is also a limited service to [[London Waterloo railway station|London Waterloo]] from Bristol Temple Meads, operated by [[South West Trains]]. The main service to London is by First Great Western to [[Paddington station]]. There are also scheduled coach links to most major UK cities.<ref name=progrep>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.progress-project.org/Progress/bristol.html
|title=Bristol (UK)
|publisher=www.progress-project.org
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref>
[[Image:Temple Meads station.jpg|thumb|left|Temple Meads station]]
The city is connected by road on an east<U+2013>west axis from [[London]] to [[West Wales]] by the [[M4 motorway]], and on a north<U+2013>southwest axis from [[Birmingham]] to [[Exeter, England|Exeter]] by the [[M5 motorway]]. Also within the county is the [[M49 motorway]], a short cut between the M5 in the south and M4 [[Severn Bridge|Severn Crossing]] in the west. The [[M32 motorway]] is a spur from the M4 to the city centre.<ref name=progrep />

The city is served by [[Bristol International Airport]] (BRS), at [[Lulsgate Plateau|Lulsgate]], which has seen substantial investments in its runway, terminal and other facilities since 2001.<ref name=progrep />

[[Image:Bristol airport overview.jpg|thumb|left|[[Bristol International Airport]], Lulsgate]]
Public transport in the city consists largely of its bus network, provided mostly by [[First Group]], formerly the [[Bristol Omnibus Company]]&nbsp;<U+2013> other services are provided by Abus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abus.co.uk/ |title=Abus |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref>
Buglers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buglercoaches.co.uk/documents/500Route.pdf |title=Buglers 500 Service |format=PDF |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> 
Ulink,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uwe.ac.uk/hsv/transport/bus.shtml |title=Ulink |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> 
and Wessex Connect.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wessexconnect.net/busroutes.aspx |title=Wessex Connect |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2008-12-20 }}</ref> 
Buses in the city have been widely criticised for being unreliable and expensive, and in 2005 First was fined for delays and safety violations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=2006-01-17c.685.4 |title=Oral Answers to Questions <U+2014> Transport |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |author=Kerry McCarthy, ''et al'' |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=17 January 2006 |year= |month= |work=British House of Commons|House of Commons |publisher=Hansard |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/4716023.stm |title=Bus firm must reduce city fleet |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-06 |work=[[BBC News Online]] | date= 25 July 2005 }}</ref>  
Private car usage in Bristol is high, and the city suffers from congestion, which costs an estimated <U+00A3>350 million per year.<ref name=ltp06.1>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Council-Democracy/Consultations/consultation-finder.en?Task=detail&Interest=0&Status=0&RecId=214 |title=Greater Bristol transport Plan |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |year= 2006 |month= |format=|work= |publisher=B&NES, Bristol City, North Somerset and South Gloucestershire councils |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref> 
Bristol is [[motorcycle]] friendly; the city recognises that motorcycle use eases congestion and encourages it by allowing motorcycles to use most of the city's bus lanes, as well as providing secure free parking.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/content/Transport-Streets/Roads-highways-and-pavements/motorcycles/motorcycles.en | work= Bristol City Council | title= Motorcycles | accessdate= 2007-09-24}}</ref>
Since 2000 the city council has included a [[light rail]] system in its [[Local Transport Plan]], but has so far been unwilling to fund the project. The city was offered [[European Union]] funding for the system, but the [[Department for Transport]] did not provide the required additional funding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/d/sus_2.pdf |title=Memorandum on Government Discrimination against Innovative Low-cost Light Rail in favour of Urban Diesel Buses | month= March | year= 2006 | accessdate=2009-01-01 |format=PDF |work=Sustraco / H.M. Treasury }}</ref> 
As well as support for public transport, there are several road building schemes supported by the local council, including re-routing and improving the [[A4174 road|South Bristol Ring Road]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gbsts.com/ |title=Greater Bristol Strategic Transport Study Chapter 6 |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |author=Atkins |authorlink= |coauthors= |date= |year= 2005 |month= |work= |publisher= |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref> 
There are also three [[park and ride]] sites serving the city, supported by the local council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/navigation/transport-and-streets/parking/park-and-ride/ |title=Park and Ride |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-08 |publisher=Bristol City Council}}</ref> 
The central part of the city has water-based transport, operated as the [[Bristol Ferry Boat]], providing leisure and commuter services on the harbour.

Bristol has  one surviving suburban railway, the [[Severn Beach Line]] to Avonmouth and [[Severn Beach]]. The [[Portishead Railway]] was closed to passengers under the [[Beeching Axe]], but was relaid in 2000<U+2013>2002 as far as the [[Royal Portbury Dock]] with a [[Strategic Rail Authority]] rail-freight grant. Plans to relay a further three miles (5&nbsp;km) of track to [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], a largely [[dormitory town]] with only one connecting road, have been discussed but there is insufficient funding to rebuild stations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2005-01-24a.134.0 |title=Bristol-Portishead Rail Link |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |author= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=24 January 2005 |work=House of Commons Debate |publisher=Hansard |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>

Despite being hilly, Bristol was named "England's first 'cycling city{{'"}} in 2008,<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/7462791.stm
|title=Bristol named first cycling city
|publisher=BBC NEWS
|date=19 June 2008
|accessdate=2009-03-16
|last=
|first=
}}
</ref> and is home to the national cycle campaigning group [[Sustrans]]. It has a number of urban cycle routes, as well as links to [[National Cycle Network]] routes to Bath and London, to Gloucester and Wales, and to the south-western peninsula of England. Cycling has grown rapidly in the city, with a 21% increase in journeys between 2001 and 2005.<ref name=ltp06.1/>

==Twin cities==
[[Image:castle.park.bristol.arp.jpg|thumb|St Peter's ruined church in Castle Park, Bristol.]]
Bristol was among the first cities to adopt the idea of [[town twinning]]. In 1947 it was twinned with [[Bordeaux]] in [[France]] and [[Hannover]], the first post-war twinning of British and [[Germany|German]] cities. Twinnings with [[Porto]], [[Portugal]] (1984), [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] (1988), [[Puerto Morazan]], [[Nicaragua]] (1989), [[Beira, Mozambique|Beira]], [[Mozambique]] (1990) and [[Guangzhou]], [[China (PRC)|China]] (2001) have followed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.gov.uk/ccm/navigation/leisure-and-culture/tourism-and-travel/town-twinning/ |title=Town twinning |dateformat=dmy|accessdate=2007-05-12 |work=Bristol City Council }}</ref>

